doc.ContractDescription: IN THE SEARCH FOR LIFE ELSEWHERE IN THE SOLAR SYSTEM, ONE PROPOSED PATH IS TO "FOLLOW THE ENERGY". ALL LIFE NEEDS ENERGY; BY LOOKING FOR PLACES WHERE ENERGY IS AVAILABLE TO SUPPORT LIFE, WE MAY BE MORE LIKELY TO FIND IT. BUT TO DO THIS, WE NEED TO UNDERSTAND THE ENERGY REQUIREMENTS OF LIFE, PARTICULARLY THE MAINTENANCE ENERGY REQUIREMENTS (THAT IS, THE ENERGY REQUIRED TO MAINTAIN LIFE WITHOUT GROWTH OR REPRODUCTION). DEEP-SEA HYDROTHERMAL VENTS PROVIDE AN EXCELLENT ANALOG FOR POTENTIAL EXTRATERRESTRIAL HABITATS; HOWEVER, THE MAINTENANCE ENERGY REQUIREMENTS OF COMMON MICROORGANISMS AT THESE SITES - PARTICULARLY ANAEROBES THAT GROW AT TEMPERATURES ABOVE 65##C - ARE POORLY-UNDERSTOOD. GEOCHEMICAL DATA FROM THESE SITES HAS BEEN USED TO MODEL HOW MUCH ENERGY IS AVAILABLE TO WHICH TYPES OF METABOLISMS, BUT THESE MODELS WERE BUILT WITHOUT A GOOD UNDERSTANDING OF HIGH-TEMPERATURE MAINTENANCE ENERGIES AND ARE IN NEED OF REFINEMENT. IN THIS PROPOSAL, WE AIM TO STUDY THE MAINTENANCE ENERGIES OF THREE ORGANISMS SAMPLED FROM HYDROTHERMAL VENT SITES AND USE THE GATHERED DATA, ALONG WITH GEOCHEMICAL DATA, TO MODEL THE HABITABILITY AND ENERGY FLUXES OF OUR FIELD SITE (AXIAL VOLCANO, IN THE NORTHEAST PACIFIC OCEAN). WE WILL TEST OUR MODEL'S ACCURACY BY COMPARING IT WITH BIOLOGICAL AND GEOCHEMICAL DATA GATHERED FROM THE FIELD SITE. MAINTENANCE ENERGIES WILL BE MEASURED BY CULTURE-BASED LABORATORY STUDIES, AND MICROBIAL ABUNDANCE IN FIELD SAMPLES WITH BE ASSESSED BY CULTURE-BASED COUNTING TECHNIQUES AND QPCR. THE HABITABILITY MODEL WE AIM TO BUILD AND TEST WILL ALLOW MORE ACCURATE CALCULATION OF BOTH HOW MUCH AND WHAT KIND OF LIFE SPECIFIC ENVIRONMENTS - EITHER EXTRATERRESTRIAL SITES, OR TERRESTRIAL ANALOGS - CAN SUPPORT. THIS WORK CAN ULTIMATELY HELP DETERMINE WHERE THE SEARCH FOR LIFE IN THE SOLAR SYSTEM SHOULD BE FOCUSED, AND HOW THAT SEARCH MIGHT BEST BE CONDUCTED, WHILE TRAINING FUTURE RESEARCHERS IN THE FIELD OF ASTROBIOLOGY.
